Mmm, Gary D's....so good....so damn good. If you're looking for a locale for a celebration dinner nonpareil in SF, you're choosing between Gary D's and also-rans. The food, service and atmosphere can't be beat unless you want to drive to Yountville, spend three times as much money and waste an hour hammer-dialing a reservation line one month in advance.

My first time writing and I'm about to bash the SF icon... oh well, here goes. I think Michelin was right to deny GD a second star. The food, I'm sorry to say, has slipped a notch or three. Let me start off with the good things though. First, the service was amazing. They struck the right cord between attentiveness and space. The wine, too, was phenomenal. I've never heard a sommelier RUN back to the table (after I shared a glass with her) and exclaim "OH MY GOD!!! this wine is AMAZING!!!" But unfortunately, I'd brought a special bottle of Harlan for my wife's birthday so all GD did was uncork it. But.... they do have a rock-star wine list and the prices are tolerable. We had a half bottle of Montrachet, recommended by the Sommelier, that was wonderful. OK - back to the food. Lobster. Gary knows what to do with lobster. We had a lobster risotto and the maine lobster with morel mushrooms and asparagus and these were both "to die for." I'm not kidding, they were up there with the best starters I've ever had. But something mysterious happens when Gary Danko starts serving meat or seafood. He goes bonko on seasoning! My seared ahi was drowning in soy sauce. My bison was pummeled with salt and my wife's herb crusted lamb was so covered in herbs that I could hardly taste the meat. It was all a shame too because GD has sourced some wonderful meats and seafood. You just can't over-season like that. It was criminal. So, service gets a star and the appetizers get two, but the mains come up with goose eggs. Too harsh for my first review?

One of the best meals of my life! What makes this place so special is the service. You can't get better dining experience elsewhere for the money. The level of service together with the great food and wine selection make for an unforgettable dining experience. The last time I was in GD was in Oct 09. I must've grinned ear to ear like an idiot the whole time we were there (out of happiness of course!) because when we got out of the place, my face hurts! So, get the foie gras, chocolate soufle, and whatever else is recommended by the waitstaff. Get the wine pairing if you can afford it. If you are only going to get 1 wine pairing, get it with the cheese course. You don't have to eat the 7 course menu. 3 or 4 is enough. You will be full (they portion the food depending on how many courses you are having) and still be alert enough to fully appreciate the distinctive flavor in each course. You don't have to do the months in advance reservation. You can take a chance, walk-in, and eat at the bar, or even the dining room if it happens to be available. The only downside to this place? it's in San Francisco, too far from the NYC metro area.

This time around, it was an early Mother's Day dinner in their 65 seat main dining room. The room makes it intimate, but it also makes for a lot of noise if there's a single very loud and obnoxious guest sitting in the center, making it impossible for any other guests to hear their own conversations. There's something on the menu for everyone, and the fact that you can do anything in any order always tempts me to get the chocolate souffle first. We started with an amuse of asparagus and ramp soup, which was green and fresh. The wine collection is extensive, and they actually had some surprisingly low mark ups on premium French wines. The menu selections are seasonal, and highlights of the choices tonight included... 1. Seared Foie Gras - get it before July 1st! 2. Risotto with Lobster, Rock shrimp, Shimeji mushrooms, Asparagus, and peas - creamy yet light - with a vegetarian option, too 3. Lobster Salad - fresh and summery ingredients with sweet mango, heart of palm, toasted pistachios, and an amazingly light, slightly sweetened green (?pistachio) cream 4. Softshell Crab - underneath is a bed of bacon grits... that's all I have to say 5. Roasted Lobster - cooked just right, tender and not overdone, with tons of flavor from the sauce of black trumpet mushrooms and taragon 6. Seared Scallops - the asparagus-pea puree was very sweet from the peas; the pickled radish and spring onions weren't my favorite, but the scallops themselves were very flavorful and seared with a nice crust 7. Lamb Loin - interesting bed of Cannellini beans, barley, and cumin - seared medium rare 8. Pork Belly and Tenderloin - with Asian flavors, slightly sweet, super tender tenderloin meat 9. Bison - medium rare with mushrooms, with a slightly tougher texture (as it should have), and I loved the green herb spaetzle underneath (I could have had a whole dish of this) 10. Macaron Ice Cream Sandwiches - rhubarb, lemon, and Irish cream 11. and of course, CHOCOLATE SOUFFLE - light, nothing like a molten chocolate cake, not too sweet, really what I was looking forward to all night... And of course mignardises to finish. Service and presentation were beautiful as prior; however, there was some lack of consistency in silverware settings, and one of the dishes was served to the wrong person initially, then handed across the table by the server (rather than formally re-presenting it to the correct person). Still - these are minute details, and the overall attitude of all of the staff was wonderful. I love the flexibility of choose-your-own menus, and they even have a separate vegetarian menu if needed Again, Gary Danko did not disappoint. I can't wait to eat my end of the meal treat tomorrow morning (sorry, ladies only!).

OMG. Ridiculous. Take me back!! I started with lobster risotto- most amazing risotto ive ever had. yum Then I had the frog legs wrapped in prosciutto- was good, but my least favorite. great customer services!

My friend Alan and I went to Gary Danko as part of my protracted moving-out-of-SF process. I'm bummed I'll be out of the country soon, because this is a place to come back to regularly. Our table wasn't actually ready when we arrived, so we parked at the bar for a half an hour or so. Multiple apologies later, we had a yummy smoked salmon on biscuit and sparkling rose to help us pass the time gratis. I also enjoyed a glass of a delicious backwards-label Rhone. Neither of us were especially hungry, so we settled for the 3-course option. I started with a light, smooth pumpkin soup (one of several seasonal options on the menu) that was tremendous, and interestingly, didn't take much like pumpkin. It came with what the menu calls "Vanilla Cornbread" but which I referred to as, "little chunk of white goodness." Alan started with a Lobster salad I didn't try. For main course (I appreciate their free-form ordering system a lot), I had the pan-roasted bison over a sauce of fall vegetables and chestnuts. It came slightly rarer than I expected from a Medium Rare order -- but I think that's a good thing. It was absolutely delicious, probably the highlight of the meal. Alan had the beef tenderloin which was also delicious, although I had had tenderloin the previous night as well. For dessert, I went seasonal again with the pumpkin spice cake with gingersnap ice cream, while Alan got the Apple bread pudding. It came with an awesome little mug of hard cider frothed to look like beer. They were both excellent, the individual tastes in the apple dish were more interesting while the pumpkin cake blended together as a whole very well. All of the food had amazing presentation, and I'm happy to say that unlike some circumstances where that level of presentation means there isn't as much attention to the food, it wasn't the case here. Every dish and every element of it were the product of great care. The service was simply superb, although probably two fewer "stop by to see how everything is" would have been fine with me too. A couple particularly well-done moments were that when we split the check by putting in two credit cards, they handed each credit card back to the right person without asking (the host noticed who claimed the reservation?) and that the host had our jackets waiting at the maitre'd's station when we stood up to leave. Outstanding in every respect. San Francisco, enjoy this place. As several folks have mentioned, you can sometimes walk in and sit at the bar without reservations (for a table, you definitely want the rez).

Finally had my first Gary Danko experience. We decided last minute b/c a friend owed me dinner so we took our chances w/ the bar. It was a Wednesday night and the place was packed when we arrive at 7.30pm! Smaller than I expected, it probably seats 70 ppl max including ~10 at the bar. Giving it 4 stars b/c of the loud volume level at the bar where we sat and the servers were stressed out during peak hours from 7.30-9pm. I know it's not the servers' fault but when it's a fancy, pricey restaurant you'd almost want they to control noise level, stress and traffic so diners can enjoy their $$$ experiences. Maitre d was very friendly. Overall ambiance and attitude is laidback and happy. Bar is first come, first serve so we expected the wait. Mostly pairs of women at the bar eating or couples. Another couple almost took the seat before us, but our attentive maitre d politely escorted them away. Whew! Before we got our seats, our bartender / server was stressed out serving the large # of ppl, so he snapped initially when I noticed 1 free seat and I politely asked if we could get 2 seats together. But later as the restaurant calmed down after 9.30pm. And he apologized a few times at the end of our meal, assuring us that the policy was to not ask seated clientele to move. Food was fantastic. I got the risotto to start. Incredible flavors and my favorite of my 4 dishes. Risotto with asparagus, small artichokes, crab and truffle oil. So decadent tasting but also very light and spring tasting. Seared scallops were my 2nd dish. Great but wouldn't call it outstanding, mainly b/c it was well-prepared but not memorable. Then I had duck meat slices, which had rhubarb on top of duck hash. The hash and rhubarb were unique! The rhubarb's tart flavor added a new dimension. This entree I liked! As we waited for dessert, we each got small scoops of passionfruit sorbet - yum! The sorbet got taken before we could finish b/c our desserts were both massive. I ordered the chocolate souffle which comes with 2 sauces (creme anglaise and dark chocolate) b/c a lady ahead of me had it and the smell was incredible. I was very happy - it came out perfectly poufed which always shows the chef's abilities. The texture was great, soft and egg white foamy. Very rich and sweet so it served my chocolate sweet tooth! But it was massive and I couldn't finish despite my best attempts. My friend got the creme brulee trio - WARNING, that is gigantic and could easily feed 3 people alone. The 3 cookies that came w/ the creme brulee were unfortunately not well made. Finally as if we weren't full enough, our server brought petit fours. Wow, I'll be coming back but w/ reservations next time.

Very class and very uppidy. They are very attentive and above all the food was awesome. I felt like Jesus Christ went down from heaven and cooked the food for us. hahaha. but seriously, if it wasn't 200+ per head, I would go back here everyday!!!

Also, if you're going for any kind of occasion at all (and really, who just pops over to Gary's unless you're celebrating something) then make sure to tell them in advance. How incredibly thoughtful - made me wish I had also told them that I had just taken the bar exam.

Unlike some of the other upper echelon (think price) restaurants on the west coast, GD manages to keep the service spot on without becoming stuffy. GD, my last meal on earth request. Enough said.

    Outstanding in every respect. Â San Francisco, enjoy this place. Â As several folks have mentioned, you can sometimes walk in and sit at the bar without reservations (for a table, you definitely want the rez).

    Finally had my first Gary Danko experience. We decided last minute b/c a friend owed me dinner so we took our chances w/ the bar. It was a Wednesday night and the place was packed when we arrive at 7.30pm! Smaller than I expected, it probably seats 70 ppl max including ~10 at the bar.

I know it's not the servers' fault but when it's a fancy, pricey restaurant you'd almost want they to control noise level, stress and traffic so diners can enjoy their $$$ experiences.

    Maitre d was very friendly. Overall ambiance and attitude is laidback and happy. Bar is first come, first serve so we expected the wait. Mostly pairs of women at the bar eating or couples. Another couple almost took the seat before us, but our attentive maitre d politely escorted them away. Whew!

    Before we got our seats, our bartender / server was stressed out serving the large # of ppl, so he snapped initially when I noticed 1 free seat and I politely asked if we could get 2 seats together. But later as the restaurant calmed down after 9.30pm. And he apologized a few times at the end of our meal, assuring us that the policy was to not ask seated clientele to move.

    Food was fantastic. I got the risotto to start. Incredible flavors and my favorite of my 4 dishes. Risotto with asparagus, small artichokes, crab and truffle oil. So decadent tasting but also very light and spring tasting. Seared scallops were my 2nd dish. Great but wouldn't call it outstanding, mainly b/c it was well-prepared but not memorable.

    Then I had duck meat slices, which had rhubarb on top of duck hash. The hash and rhubarb were unique! The rhubarb's tart flavor added a new dimension. This entree I liked!

    As we waited for dessert, we each got small scoops of passionfruit sorbet - yum! The sorbet got taken before we could finish b/c our desserts were both massive. I ordered the chocolate souffle which comes with 2 sauces (creme anglaise and dark chocolate) b/c a lady ahead of me had it and the smell was incredible. I was very happy - it came out perfectly poufed which always shows the chef's abilities. The texture was great, soft and egg white foamy. Very rich and sweet so it served my chocolate sweet tooth! But it was massive and I couldn't finish despite my best attempts. My friend got the creme brulee trio - WARNING, that is gigantic and could easily feed 3 people alone. The 3 cookies that came w/ the creme brulee were unfortunately not well made.

    Finally as if we weren't full enough, our server brought petit fours. Wow, I'll be coming back but w/ reservations next time.
